Scripts

There are 3 writing system used in Japanese namely the Kanji, Hiragana and the Katakana scripts.

Kanji

Kanji was based on Chinese characters which represents a word and a meaning.

L5

L4

L3

L2

L1

Hiragana

Hiragana is a phonetic script used to represent Japanese sound.

Katakana

Katakana is a phonetic script used to represent Foreign loan words.

IC.1.0: Connectives

Connectives appear at the beginning of an independent sentence and indicates how that sentence relates to the previous one.

MC.1.0: I-Adjectives

Adjectives are words that describe nouns and pronouns.

Structure

‚ë† Forms

I-Adj (Plain Form - Non Past)
„Éªyasui  ‚á¢   yasui
I-Adj (Polite Form - Non Past)
„Éªyasui  ‚á¢   yasui desu
I-Adj (Plain Form - Past Tense)
„Éªyasui  ‚á¢   yasukatta
I-Adj (Polite Form - Past Tense)
„Éªyasui  ‚á¢   yasukatta desu
I-Adj (Plain Form - Negative)
„Éªyasui  ‚á¢   yasukunai
I-Adj (Polite Form - Negative)
„Éªyasui  ‚á¢   yasukunai desu
„Éªyasui  ‚á¢   yasuku arimasen
I-Adj (Plain Form - Past Negative)
„Éªyasui  ‚á¢   yasuku nakatta
I-Adj (Polite Form - Past Negative)
„Éªyasui  ‚á¢   yasuku nakatta desu
„Éªyasui  ‚á¢   yasuku arimasen deshita
I-Adj.ad (Adverbial Form)
„Éªyasui  ‚á¢   yasuku
I-Adj (Connective Form)
„Éªyasui  ‚á¢   yasukute

MC.2.0: Na-Adjectives

Adjectives are words that describe nouns and pronouns.

Structure

‚ë† Forms

Na-Adj (Plain Form - Non Past)
„Éªgenki  ‚á¢   genki da

„Éªgenki  ‚á¢   genki desu

MC.6.0: Demonstratives

Demonstratives are words that indicate entities to which a speaker is referring.

ko

kore this„Éªthis one

kono (+noun) this (noun)

MC.7.0: Interrogatives

Interrogatives are words used to ask questions or the words that represents the thing we don‚Äôt know.

‚ë† Exceptions: 

1. Ikaga is formal way of "how".
2. Ikutsu mo means several with positive verb.
3. Itsumo means always.
4. Itsumademo means forever.

‚ë° Indefinite: 

1. „Å†„Çå„Åã„Åå„Åß„Çì„Çè„Çí„Åó„Åæ„Åó„Åü

3. „ÅÑ„Åè„Å§„Åã„Åã„Çè„Åõ„Å¶„ÅÑ„Åü„Å†„Åë„Åæ„Åô„Åã
1. Somebody telephoned
2. Shall we go somewhere?
3. May i buy some

‚ë¢ Negatives: 

1. Daremo and nanimo are used only with a negative verb or adjective.
2. Others may use with either negative or positive.
1. „Å†„Çå„ÇÇ„Åç„Åæ„Åõ„Çì„Åß„Åó„Åü                                                 
2. „Å©„ÅÜ„Å´„ÇÇ„Åß„Åç„Å™„ÅÑ„Å®„Åä„ÇÇ„ÅÑ„Åæ„Åô

MC.8.0: Nominalizer

MC.10: Affixes

Prefix

A prefix is a short element that is attached to the beginning of a word to add an additional meaning to or to change the meaning of the word.

Suffix

A suffix is a short element that is attached to the end of a word to change the meaning of or to add an additional meaning to the word.

EC.1.0: Verbs

Verbs are a words that expresses the physical or mental activities carried out by the subject of a sentence.

Groups

Types

TransitiveAction Transitive verbs are verbs that take a direct object. They express what an agent does.

Sentence Construction

Simple Sentences

‚ë† Nominal Sentences:

„ÉªNoun‚í∂ + Noun‚í∑ + Copula: ‚í∑ describes or identifies ‚í∂
„Éª„Ç∏„Éß„É≥„Åï„Çì„Åå„Ç¢„É°„É™„Ç´„Åò„Çì„Åß„Åô

‚ë° Adjectival Sentences: I-Adjective

„ÉªAdjective‚í∂ + Noun‚í∑: ‚í∑ describes ‚í∂
„ÉªÁ©∫„ÅåÈùí„ÅÑ 
„ÉªSora ga aoi 
„ÉªThe sky is blue

‚ë¢ Adjectival Sentences: Na-Adjective

„ÉªAdjective‚í∂ + Noun‚í∑ + Copula: ‚í∑ describes ‚í∂
„ÉªÂú∞‰∏ãÈâÑ„Åå‰æøÂà©„Å† 
„ÉªChikatetsu ga benri da 
„ÉªThe subway is convenient

‚ë£ Verbal Sentences: Intransitive Verb

„ÉªTopic„ÉªSubject‚í∂ + Verb‚í∑: ‚í∑ describes the state of ‚í∂ 
„ÉªÊ°ú„Åï„Çì„ÅåÊù•„Åü

‚ë§ Verbal Sentences: Transitive Verb

„ÉªTopic„ÉªSubject‚í∂ + Object‚í∑ + Verb‚í∏: ‚í∂ does the action ‚í∏ to ‚í∑
„ÉªÂÖàÁîü„ÅØÊéàÊ•≠„ÇíÂßã„ÇÅ„Åü

‚ë• Topic-Comment Sentences:

„ÉªTopic‚í∂ + Comment‚í∑: ‚í∑ describes ‚í∂
„ÉªÊó•Êú¨„ÅØÊò•„Å®Áßã„Åå„ÅÑ„ÅÑ

PT1.0: Particles

Particles are short functional words that are attached to nouns and indicates its grammatical role.

Concept
